oc:kn_0bf4bace a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When selecting DCF model type based on company characteristics" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Support three model types: Standard DCF (5-year + terminal), Two-Stage DCF (high growth + stable), and Three-Stage DCF (growth + transition + maturity) to handle different company lifecycle stages." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Different companies require different projection frameworks to accurately capture their growth trajectory." .

oc:kn_119881d2 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building DCF models for companies with anticipated capital structure changes" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Standard DCF assumes constant WACC throughout the projection period, which may not reflect reality for companies with changing capital structures or risk profiles." ;
    oc:hasRationale "A static WACC can materially misvalue companies undergoing leverage changes, IPOs, or significant deleveraging." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_5a86ec79 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before starting DCF model construction" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Verify that historical financial data (3-5 years of revenue, EBITDA, capex, D&A), shares outstanding, and industry context are available before building the model." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Incomplete financial data leads to unreliable projections and assumptions based on insufficient evidence." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_6a66de33 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SecurityImplication ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating any DCF valuation report" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Always include a disclaimer that the model is for educational and informational purposes only and does not constitute investment advice." ;
    oc:hasRationale "DCF models produce forward-looking estimates that carry inherent uncertainty; omitting disclaimers creates legal and regulatory risk." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_b93889b5 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When presenting DCF valuation results" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never present a single-point DCF estimate without sensitivity analysis. Terminal value typically represents 60-80% of total enterprise value, making the output extremely sensitive to WACC and terminal growth assumptions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Without sensitivity analysis, users may treat the output as precise when it is inherently a range estimate driven by assumptions." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_d79713e3 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When calculating terminal value using Gordon Growth Model" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Terminal growth rate must be ≤ GDP growth rate (typically 2-3%) and must be less than WACC for the Gordon Growth Model to produce a finite result." ;
    oc:hasRationale "If terminal growth equals or exceeds WACC, the formula FCF/(WACC-g) produces undefined or negative values, breaking the entire valuation." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_eb9b6794 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "After completing DCF valuation" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Cross-check DCF-derived intrinsic value with comparable multiples (P/E, EV/EBITDA) as a sanity check. If values diverge significantly, revisit assumptions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Multiples provide market-based reality checks that can reveal flawed DCF assumptions, especially around growth rates and margins." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_f89b8c08 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When user requests DCF for pre-revenue or deeply unprofitable companies" ;
    oc:directiveContent "DCF methodology is not suitable for early-stage unprofitable companies where cash flows are negative and difficult to project reliably." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Negative free cash flows with uncertain timing to profitability make DCF outputs unreliable; use comparable company analysis or venture capital methods instead." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

